s</i> ‘lamb’, and in medieval art she is often depicted with a lamb (the lamb of God). See also English   Annis  .","American shortened (and altered) form of rare Greek metronymics <b>Agnidis</b> or <b>Agniadis</b>, both derived from the female personal name <i>Hagnē</i> (see 1 above), or of patronymics like   Anagnostopoulos   (compare   Agnew   4)."]}]},{"name":"Raoul","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Ralph</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Yves","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from a Germanic personal name representing a short form of various compound names containing the element <i>iv</i> ‘yew’. The final <i>-s</i> is the mark of the Old French nominative case. The name was introduced to Britain from France at the time of the Norman Conquest.  See also  Ivo ."],"variants":[{"name":"Yvon","meanings":["from a Germanic personal name representing a short form of various compound names containing the element <i>iv</i> ‘yew’. The final <i>-s</i> is the mark of the Old French nominative case. The name was introduced to Britain from France at the time of the Norman Conquest.  See also  Ivo ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Raoul Yves de Nesle was born in 1052, in Nesle, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Drogon de Nesle, was 23 and his mother, Hortense DE COUCY, was 17. He married Raintrude de Soissons about 1098, in Brugge, West Flanders, Belgium. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1121, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1052–1121":"1052–1121","1060–1121":"1060–1121","1065–1117":"1065–1117","1078–Female":"1078–Surnud","1108–1160":"1108–1160","1030–1077":"1030–1077","1035–Female":"1035–Surnud","1077":"1077","1121":"1121","1065":"1065","1052":"1052","1030":"1030","1160":"1160","1060":"1060","1117":"1117","about 1108":"umbes 1108","1035":"1035","1078":"1078","about 1098":"u